{"key":"post-10998039","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10998039</id>\n<content>Yes, cakes can be misted directly.&amp;nbsp; In the early days it was thought it took a sealed up terrarium to maintain humidity.&amp;nbsp; They also had poor to mediocre performance back then.&amp;nbsp; We now know that fresh air exchange is a major pinning trigger, and that you can mist cakes directly as long as they don't sit there wet in still and stale air.&amp;nbsp; In fact, you NEED to mist your substrates to replace the moisture that evaporates, which is another major pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; We've come a long way in knowledge of mushroom cultivation in the last dozen years or so.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To answer your question, drip shields are not needed, and in fact counterproductive.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10998212</next>\n<prev>10996447</prev>\n<first>10996343</first>\n<last>10998212</last>\n<when>1252081207</when>\n<utime>09/04/09 07:20 PM</utime>\n</post>"}